  "title": "More heterosexual spread of HTLV-III virus seen",
  "abstract": "Welcoming participants to the recent International Conference on Acquired Immunodeficiency Syndrome (AIDS) in Atlanta, Department of Health and Human Services Secretary Margaret M. Heckler said: \"For individuals in every country who fall within the risk categories, AIDS is an enormously serious disease. We must conquer it for their sake. We must conquer it as well before it affects the heterosexual population and threatens the health of our general population.\" Unfortunately, and perhaps despite all good intentions, not only was the secretary's phraseology offensive to many—but her timing also may have been off. Several speakers at the conference presented evidence that heterosexual transmission of AIDS is something to reckon with right now. While it has been accepted for some time that female sexual partners of men who are in the high-risk groups for AIDS—bisexuals, intravenous (IV) drug abusers, and persons with hemophilia—are at increased risk of contracting the disease, the epidemiologically",
